						               													<description>In &amp;#231;&amp;#142;&amp;#139;&amp;#229;&amp;#174;&amp;#174;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#233;&amp;#163;&amp;#190;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#138;&amp;#231;&amp;#181;&amp;#181;&amp;#229;&amp;#184;&amp;#171; (&amp;#197;&amp;#140;ky&amp;#197;&amp;#171; No Kazari Eshi), roughly translated as Royal Palace Decorative Painter, the players are each painters who have been hired by the royal family to paint the Monochrome Palace.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player receives a die showing different colors and one showing different numbers.  The players also get a sheet which shows the outline of a painting which they will be coloring in during the game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;On a turn, the players simultaneously choose the faces for their dice and then reveal.  Beginning with players who chose the smaller number, players can color in sections on their sheet corresponding to the number and color chosen as their dice values.  However, as the resolution proceeds to higher valued die, you will not be able to fill in colors that were chosen by players with lower numbers, and other similar concerns.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game includes royal request cards that can grant points at the end of the game (e.g. have the most sectors of a certain color) or during the game (e.g. be the first do have one section of each color).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game ends after 12 rounds, and the player with the most points wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
